3. Data Cleaning

Remove Duplicates

cyclistic_data <- cyclistic_data %>% distinct()

Check for Missing Values

colSums(is.na(cyclistic_data))

Ensure Correct Data Types

cyclistic_data$ride_length <- as.numeric(gsub("[^0-9.]", "", cyclistic_data$ride_length))

4. Data Analysis & Visualization

4.1 Average Ride Duration per User Type

avg_ride_duration <- cyclistic_data %>%
  group_by(usertype) %>%
  summarise(avg_ride_length = mean(ride_length, na.rm = TRUE))

print(avg_ride_duration)
## # A tibble: 2 × 2
##   usertype   avg_ride_length
##   <chr>                <dbl>
## 1 Customer             4637.
## 2 Subscriber           1188.
# Plot
ggplot(avg_ride_duration, aes(x = usertype, y = avg_ride_length, fill = usertype)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("Customer" = "#1f77b4", "Subscriber" = "#6baed6")) +
  labs(title = "Average Ride Duration per User Type", x = "User Type", y = "Average Ride Length (minutes)") +
  theme_minimal()

4.2 Busiest Riding Hours per User Type

cyclistic_data$hour_of_day <- as.numeric(substr(cyclistic_data$start_time, 12, 13))

busiest_hours <- cyclistic_data %>%
  group_by(usertype, hour_of_day) %>%
  summarise(ride_count = n()) %>%
  arrange(usertype, hour_of_day)
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'usertype'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
# Plot
ggplot(busiest_hours, aes(x = hour_of_day, y = ride_count, color = usertype, group = usertype)) +
  geom_line(size = 1) +  
  geom_point(size = 2) + 
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 23, by = 1)) +  
  scale_color_manual(values = c("Subscriber" = "#1f77b4", "Customer" = "#ff7f0e")) +
  labs(title = "Busiest Riding Hours per User Type",
       x = "Hour of the Day", y = "Ride Count", color = "User Type") +
  theme_minimal()
## Warning: Using `size` aesthetic for lines was deprecated in ggplot2 3.4.0.

4.3 Most Popular Ride Start Stations by User Type

top_stations <- cyclistic_data %>%
  group_by(usertype, from_station_name) %>%
  summarise(ride_count = n()) %>%
  arrange(usertype, desc(ride_count)) %>%
  group_by(usertype) %>%
  slice_head(n = 10)
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'usertype'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
# Plot
ggplot(top_stations, aes(x = reorder(from_station_name, ride_count), y = ride_count, fill = usertype)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  coord_flip() +  
  facet_wrap(~ usertype) +  
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("Subscriber" = "#1f77b4", "Customer" = "#6baed6")) +  
  labs(title = "Top 10 Most Popular Start Stations by User Type",
       x = "Start Station", y = "Ride Count") +
  theme_minimal()

4.4 Most Popular Ride End Stations by User Type

top_end_stations <- cyclistic_data %>%
  group_by(usertype, to_station_name) %>%
  summarise(ride_count = n()) %>%
  arrange(usertype, desc(ride_count)) %>%
  group_by(usertype) %>%
  slice_head(n = 10)
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'usertype'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
# Plot
ggplot(top_end_stations, aes(x = reorder(to_station_name, ride_count), y = ride_count, fill = usertype)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  coord_flip() +  
  facet_wrap(~ usertype) +  
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("Subscriber" = "#1f77b4", "Customer" = "#6baed6")) +  
  labs(title = "Top 10 Most Popular End Stations by User Type",
       x = "End Station", y = "Ride Count") +
  theme_minimal()

5. Conclusion

  • Annual members and casual riders exhibit different riding behaviors.
  • Subscribers have shorter ride durations, while casual riders take longer trips.
  • Peak riding hours differ for each user type.
  • Popular start and end stations provide insights for targeted marketing.

This analysis provides valuable insights for Cyclistic’s marketing team to encourage casual riders to become members.
